est/api/2/issue/12363719/comment/12476236","id":"12476236","author":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=rhillegas","name":"rhillegas","emailAddress":"rhillegas at apache dot org","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Rick Hillegas","active":true},"body":"This is an interesting topic which I would like to understand better. It seems that there is a great deal of Derby's public API which is not visible in the relatively small number of classes which we expose in the javadoc shipped with our distributions. For instance, error messages and command line arguments are part of Derby's public API which we document in our user guides but not in the javadoc.\r\n\r\nI think it is reasonable to test that Derby conforms to the behavior documented in the user guides. Is the issue here the actual imports? Is there a best practice for eliminating these imports but still verifying that the code agrees with the user guides?","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/user?username=rhillegas","name":"rhillegas","emailAddress":"rhillegas at apache dot org","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?avatarId=10452","24x24":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=small&avatarId=10452","16x16":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=xsmall&avatarId=10452","32x32":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/useravatar?size=medium&avatarId=10452"},"displayName":"Rick Hillegas","active":true},"created":"2007-02-27T17:25:49.256+0000","updated":"2007-02-27T17:25:49.256+0000"},{"self":"https://issues.apache.org/jira/rest/api/2/issue/12363719/comment/12476299","id":"12476299